Using Machine Learning on HAR Sensors to Predict Activity Execution Correctness

Kuan Siew Weng

11 June 2015

Synopsis

Many people now regularly use personal activity tracking devices such as Jawbone Up, Nike FuelBand, and Fitbit to quantify how much of a particular activity they do, but these devices rarely quantify how well they do those activities.

The goal of this project is to demonstrate how machine learning classification models may be trained to use the accelerometer and gyroscope data collected from such sensor devices, for predicting how well a particular activity was performed.

Source Dataset

The dataset used for this project is the Weight Lifting Exercise Dataset, which contains the sensor measurements taken from six young healthy participants when they performed one set of 10 repetitions of the Unilateral Dumbbell Biceps Curl in five different fashions: - Class A (performed exactly according to the specification) - Class B (throwing the elbows to the front) - Class C (lifting the dumbbell only halfway) - Class D (lowering the dumbbell only halfway) - Class E (throwing the hips to the front)

More information is available from the website here: http://groupware.les.inf.puc-rio.br/har (see the section on the Weight Lifting Exercise Dataset).

Reference: Velloso, E.; Bulling, A.; Gellersen, H.; Ugulino, W.; Fuks, H. Qualitative Activity Recognition of Weight Lifting Exercises. Proceedings of 4th International Conference in Cooperation with SIGCHI (Augmented Human 13) . Stuttgart, Germany: ACM SIGCHI, 2013.

Cleaning Data

# strip all new_window=yes rows, NA-valued and raw_timestamp columns
train_clean <- train_raw[train_raw$new_window == "no", ]
train_clean <- train_clean[,colSums(is.na(train_clean)) != nrow(train_clean)]
train_clean <- train_clean[,-c(1:7)]

Partitioning Training Dataset for Cross-Validation

# split train_clean to train and xval for cross validation 
in_train <- createDataPartition(y=train_clean$classe, p=0.70, list=FALSE)
train_ds <- train_clean[in_train,]
xval_ds <- train_clean[-in_train,]

Train a full Random Forest Model

set.seed(33833)
no_of_folds <- 7

# Setting up the seeds for TrainControl to ensure reproducibility 
seeds <- vector(mode = "list", length = no_of_folds)
for(i in 1:no_of_folds) seeds[[i]] <- sample.int(1000, 3)
seeds[[no_of_folds + 1]] <- sample.int(1000, 1)

trc <- trainControl(method="cv", number=no_of_folds, seeds=seeds)

rf_fit <- train(classe ~ ., method="rf", data=train_ds, ntrees=150, prox=FALSE,
                trControl=trc)
## Loading required package: randomForest
## randomForest 4.6-10
## Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
print(rf_fit$finalModel)

Examine the Variable Importance to reduce non-principal and correlated Features

rf_vi <- varImp(rf_fit)
plot(rf_vi)

imp <- rf_vi$importance
